annotations:
In my self made isolation, you’re my only inspiration
 When the mirror says I’m ugly and if anybody loves me, it’s a lie

When you have crushingly low self-esteem, like Baby Queen references here with the mirror telling her she’s ugly, you may retreat into emotional fantasies to avoid being hurt by the potential reality.

In this case, because she believes the mirror tells her “that if anybody loves her, it’s a lie,” she finds comfort in indulging in a mental fantasy of a relationship with this individual she has romanticized.

However, this mental fantasy that reflects her innermost desire is beginning to consume her. She’s so obsessed with idea of this man and being in a relationship with him that she can’t escape it even when she wants to.
If I could I’d cry, we’ve got incompatible star signs

Baby Queen has said she doesn’t really believe in astrology, but has also described herself as “a Leo to a T.”

“We’re actually really nice people. We just like attention,” she told Insider. “It’s like, I will buy everyone at this entire bar a shot tonight and be broke for the rest of the month, just so that you can have a good night. But you have to compliment me, too.”

If she sees Leo as an inherently generous star sign, perhaps her crush is “incompatible” because he’s selfish. This line also emphasizes that her love is one-sided; he’s not paying her enough attention.
Up in my imagination, I rehearse our conversations
She has imaginary conversations with the object of her obsession because she’s thinking about them obsessively.

I met your ghost, he followed me
 Down to the coast of Dover Beach
 I talk to you in poetry
 You stole the view of Dover Beach
 I met your ghost, he followed me
 Down to the coast of Dover Beach
 I scream at you in poetry

Bella Latham, who wrote “Dover Beach” states, “I was kind of pissed that I went to look at the beach, all I could think about was this person, hence the lyric "you stole the view of Dover Beach.” It’s another internal struggle with my own insecurities and a sort of acceptance of the fact that I can’t escape my daydreams of this person, even if I go to a different place.”

description.plain:
This song was the last single before the release of Baby Queen’s debut ep, “Medicine” on which it appears.

Discussing her song “Buzzkill,” Baby Queen revealed her inspiration for the song, stating:
“But now there’s a song coming out at the end of the year that I think I’m never going to out-write — it’s about Jodie Comer from Killing Eve. And the day that ‘Buzzkill’ came out, we had this idea for a song that is coming out next year and I remember coming home from the studio that day and being like: ‘Fuck! It’s also a song about Jodie Comer’. I can’t fall in love with anyone else.”

In January of 2021, singer Courtney Love posted a video of Baby Queen performing on her Instagram, the caption including “‘Want Me’ immaculate. Shitty French accent has me laughing so hard..”

annotations: Like a painting or a poster of a teenage crush

It’s very common for teenage girls to cover their walls with pictures and posters of whatever band member, actor, or musician they have a crush on.

In saying that she will put them up against a wall, Baby Queen says that this person is their obsessive teenage crush.

And I stay home ’cause all my friends are getting bored of me
 I find a way to fit your name in every sentence that I speak

In an interview with [Coup De Main Magazine] (http://coupdemainmagazine.com/baby-queen/17370) she divulges:

I’m a very obsessive person; I always have been, and I find obsession as a concept to be totally fascinating. Any relationship I’ve been in has been born out of some degree of obsession (which is not a positive thing; it’s definitely a childhood trauma situation lol), and I find I’m the most inspired when I have something or somebody to focus on. In my experience, when you are constantly thinking about a person or a goal, it’s only natural to look at everything around you through the lens of how it relates to the object of your affection. If I like somebody, I don’t want to talk about anything else, so I will just direct the conversation back to them, which is probably incredibly annoying for my friends.

annotations:
White lies are coloured by context
 And oh my God, I’ve lost my innocence
‘White lies’ references Nick’s ignorance to his sexuality before he met Charlie. ‘I’ve lost my innocence’ demonstrates how meeting Charlie catalysed the discovery of his identity.
I speak in grey

Starting the song with the word ‘grey’ is a juxtaposition to the title ‘colours of you’. This shows how at the start, both Nick and Charlie’s lives are unfulfilled. As the song progresses, and mentions other colours like ‘red orange yellow green blue’, it demonstrates how the relationship has brought out their true personalities and revealed things they didn’t initially know about themselves, such as Nick’s bisexuality.
Purple and blue

Purple and blue are two of the three colours on the bisexual flag (alongside pink), so highlighting these specific colours references Nick’s bisexuality and how Charlie is ‘covered in the colours’ of Nick as they begin their relationship.
You look at me and the darkness leaves

Kit Connor, the actor of Nick Nelson in the Netflix series Heartstopper, has stated in various interviews that this song is written from his character’s perspective.

Therefore the “darkness” could be referring to who he was before and that he is becoming more himself when he is with Charlie.
You’ve changed my life into something I no longer recognise

This could mean how Charlie changed Nick’s life when they first met. Charlie helped Nick discover who he truly is and help him become accepting of it. He showed him what it’s like to have a true friend while simultaneously showing him what love should look and feel like.
Purple, pink and indigo too

As this song is about Nick figuring out his own diversity, at the final chorus we can actually have a reference to the bi flag with these three colors, being by obvious consequence a reference to Nick´s bisexuality. The Bisexual flag colors are pink, purple, and indigo, (you could say magenta instead of pink, that’s kinda why I think is just a reference and not an actual explicit mention of the flag).
And even as a personal guess, it could even be about how he didn’t discovered it in a simple easy way, being that the reason the colors of the flag are not in actual order. That would make even more sense if we pointed out how in both chorus 1 and 2 there´s only “purple and blue”, but finally in the last chorus, we finally have all of the three colors that make the flag, as if he finally discovered himself.

Red, orange, yellow, green, blue
 Purple, pink and indigo too

As the song is all talking about Nick´s and Charlie´s new relationship, specifically about how Nick is discovering and getting covered in all of these new colors, the bridge works as a reference to a rainbow, and as we all know, rainbows are usually related to the lgbt+ community and their diversity. Referencing at the time, how Nick is now covered in this completely new diverse world of possibilities, labels, and acceptance since he is no longer just “speaking in grey”

I used to see the world in black and white
 Now I, I

These lines seem a reference to Nick’s discovery of his bisexuality, as the dichotomy of black and white can be extrapolated to that of homo/heterosexuality.

Since society always presents itself in binary terms, it can be difficult to acknowledge one’s sexuality (or identity) when you don’t fit either of the terms.

description.plain:
“Buzzkill” is the 4th track of artist Babyqueens EP “Medicine.”
In an interview with NME, she revealed the songwriting process:
“It was actually a stage in my life, but I wrote the song after this mad night out in east London. It was meant to be great vibes and I started crying. My friends were like: ‘You’re so young, chill out. Life’s so good!’ It was almost like [they were] asking me out of my anxiety spell. I have a guilt complex with partying and I was going through a break-up then, too. I went home and was like [sings the melody that leads to the chorus]: ‘I don’t wanna be a buzzkill’. The chorus came that night, but the song was actually written over a few months.”
Further, she said:
“Without getting too deep, I feel a lot of responsibility to a lot of people in my life and to always look after them and make sure they’re happy. I also have this thing in my head where I’m like: ‘I want to be a good person'. I don’t really party that much anymore, but I was partying really heavily during that time of writing ‘Buzzkill’. Do you know when you wake up and just regret your whole life? You feel like an awful human being and I started to pre-empt the guilt before the next morning and be like: ‘Oh my god, I’m horrible’.”
The video was directed by the video production duo Bedroom (beabadoobee, The 1975).

annotations:
In the hours when it falls, I try to comprehend
 All the meaning in emotion, I’m emotionless
An effect that depression can have on people is making them feel numb, empty or emotionless. It’s very hard to comprehend your emotions when you can’t feel anything.
Why do I take these drugs? Why do I go too far?
This is a reference to another of Baby Queen’s songs, “These Drugs”.
I’m thinking about you and you’re thinking about sex

This lyric shows us that Baby Queen was possibly in a relationship in which she was genuinely interested and had real feelings toward this person, but the other person was just in it for the sex. She is dreaming about this dreamy person who she is falling for, but the other person is just dreaming about doing it with her.

I’m thinking about you and you’re thinking about sex
 I’m thinking about you and you’re thinking about sex
 I’m thinking about you and you’re thinking about sex

“Latham said she’s "mostly dated men,” though she’s explored queer desire in her music. “Want Me,” for example, was inspired by her crush on “Killing Eve” star Jodie Comer; and fans recently christened “Raw Thoughts” a “bi anthem” after Latham revealed its erotic lyrics are “not about a man.”“

description.plain: When the song first played on ‘BBC Radio 1’s Future Sounds’, Baby Queen said “This is a song called ‘Nobody Really Cares’ which I wrote about the fact that we do seem to care so much about what other people think of us. When in reality, people are probably way more concerned about how they’re being perceived by everybody else. And basically, it’s just really liberating to know that nobody cares as much as you think they do and you should just do whatever makes you happy.”
